audit-b14: cdx defensive sweep — strncpy -> strscpy

Mechanical rewrite across 9 cdx TUs converting all remaining strncpy()
callsites to strscpy(). strncpy() is deprecated in 6.6+ kernel string
handling (does not guarantee NUL termination, NUL-pads remainder);
strscpy() guarantees NUL termination within the destination bound and
returns the length copied (or -E2BIG on truncation).

Coverage (28 sites total in the cdx kernel module):

  control_pppoe.c     2 sites (in_ifname copies for IP / relay paths)
  control_bridge.c    2 sites (in_ifname / out_ifname; B6 missed
                              these because they use length=IF_NAME_SIZE
                              not sizeof(...))
  control_tunnel.c    1 site
  control_tx.c        1 site
  cdx_mc_query.c      4 sites (multicast input/output device strings
                              for IPv4 + IPv6 snapshots)
  dpa_control_mc.c   10 sites (ingress_iface, ucIngressIface, ucInterface,
                              members[].if_info)
  devman.c            5 sites (iface_info->name across get_eth/wlan/
                              tunnel/oh setters)
  devoh.c             2 sites (port_name, iface_info->name)
  layer2.c            1 site  (gOnif_DB[i].name)

All destinations are interface-name char arrays, NOT fixed-record
binary fields — none depend on the NUL-padding behaviour of strncpy.
strncpy_from_user() callsites in cdx/dpa_test.c are NOT touched
(different API; strncpy_from_user() always NUL-terminates).

No behaviour change on the well-formed input path. Truncation semantics
change from "may emit a non-terminated string" to "always NUL-terminate
within the dst bound" — strictly safer.

